      "nzzSummary": {
        "de_CH": "",
        "en_US": "- Tensions between France and Algeria are rising, as Algeria's government has refused to accept its deported nationals, including criminals.\n- Algerian «Harraga» are migrants in France who have destroyed their identity documents to conceal their origins. Unable to return, many face dismal lives on the margins of French society.\n- France is threatening to cancel a migration agreement with Algeria, further straining the already tense relations.\n"
      },
      "seoDescription": "Tens of thousands of Algerians are living in France without legal permission. But the Algiers government is refusing to take back even dangerous criminals. The dispute threatens to upend a historic migration pact.",
      "leadText": "Tens of thousands of Algerians are living in France without legal permission. But the Algiers government is steadfastly refusing to take back even dangerous criminals. Paris is now threatening to withdraw from a historic migration pact.",
      "germanyRelevant": false,
      "publicationLastUpdated": "2025-03-06T12:24:02.228Z",
      "nzzArticleSnippet": "Tens of thousands of Algerians are living in France without legal permission. But the Algiers government is steadfastly refusing to take back even dangerous criminals. Paris is now threatening to withdraw from a historic migration pact.",
